diff:1664468525:1664468525:=1,116d0%0a%3c (:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0a%3c Status: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!{$:Category}]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Uncommon Consonants: Comparing English and Xhosa%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: leonlu%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Uncommon Consonants: Comparing English and Xhosa%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Xhosa belongs to the Bantu language family and is commonly spoken in South Africa. It has about 7.9 million native speakers and another 11 million second language speakers. It is also one of the official languages of South Africa. %0a%3c %0a%3c In terms of phonological typology, there are a few things that Xhosa differs from English in several ways. Namely, it has a tones system, whereas English has none; it also has a number of unusual consonants that English speakers are probably unfamiliar with. We will focus on Xhosa's unusual consonants. %0a%3c %0a%3c One unusual consonant Xhosa has is the voiced bilabial implosive [ɓ], which is produced by moving the glottis. Xhosa also has 18 click sounds. Click sounds are rare as they are almost only found in languages in Southern Africa. Click sounds are produced by suction at a certain location in the mouth. English speakers might sometimes produce click sounds to, for example, communicate with pets. In Xhosa, however, 18 distinct click sounds are involved in the consonant inventory, and 10%25 of the language's basic words contain a click sound. %0a%3c %0a%3c The click sounds can be described by the manner of articulation and the articulation, as listed below:%0a%3c %0a%3c Places of click consonants:%0a%3c %0a%3c - Dental [ǀ]%0a%3c - Lateral [ǁ]%0a%3c - Alveolar [!]%0a%3c %0a%3c Manners of click consonants (where ◌ refers to the clicks in the previous list):%0a%3c %0a%3c - Ejective [k◌ʼ]%0a%3c - Aspirated [k◌ʰ]%0a%3c - slack voice [ɡ̊◌ʱ]%0a%3c - nasal [ŋ◌]%0a%3c - slack-voice nasal [ŋ◌ʱ]%0a%3c - prenasalized ejected [ŋ◌ʼ]%0a%3c %0a%3c For example, Xhosa is pronounced [kǁʰóːsa], which contains the aspirated lateral click [kǁʰ]. %0a%3c %0a%3c There have been attempts to build speech recognition systems for Xhosa, and researchers have acknowledged the challenge of a more complex consonant inventory.%0a%3c %0a%3c A question worth investigating is how click consonants are developed in the first place, given how rare it is geographically.%0a%3c %0a%3c Ref%0a%3c %0a%3c 1. https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.2989/16073610509486401%0a%3c 2. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xhosa_language%0a%3c 3. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Click_consonant?oldformat=true%0a%3c 4. https://doi.org/10.1159/000066068%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c You must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a%3c !!Change artic